subtitle.$: Some pictures of the first year in our first house!

summary.$: View from our master bedroom
View from the master bedroom. You can almost see the lake!
Our storage closet *inside* the huge laundry room
And so begins the moving process. This is our apartment living room.
Best picture of the front of the house yet
The geek is actually The Handy Man for the duration of this story
We ended up not liking that color. And this is why we got 14 pints of just samples!
Finished! The difference that lamp makes is amazing. Very bright! Now if I could only get a dimmer that works for it!
Keri cracked open the first color in the first room. We're off!
Done with the first coat of the first room!
We're replacing all of the light fixtures in the house :)
Now tell me this is not an AWESOME color!
The story behind installing this fan is full of drama, tragedy and two electrocutions. Sorry again, Josh!
The new medicine cabinet! :) Thanks for installing it, Josh
How awesome does this look? Vivian and Keri painted the basement this great color while I tried to electrocute Josh with the fan
I really like this color
The first snowfall of the year and with our new house!
Pretty cute row of houses, huh?
And there is our place!
Our helpers taping the living room and dinning room for its paint job :)
The first wall. GREAT color :)
So much for getting at most 1 inch in the evening! Weather forecasters were a little bit off!
The remains of the terrible banister that separated our living room and dinning room. Cut most of it up before dremmel died!
And here is the finished product! OK, ignore the mess. Just imagine how awesome it will look with furniture :)
Those are our brand new hardwoods! Brazillian Walnut!
Mandy is liking these windows :)
Our master bedroom! This was the hardest room to paint and I really love this orange
If you rotate this around, it just looks like I am standing. Really should not have put the 2k lb of hardwoods so close to the wall!
MOVING DAY!! Cancelled due to the worst blizzard in over a decade, so we decided to get the dog to do a faceplant in the snow instead!
Before...
after
Behold the pile of snow in our new front yard!
Cute, huh?
Yeah, it snowed a lot
It REALLY snowed a lot
If you notice the kitchen entry - yeah, that is all of the stuff that goes in the living room!
Looking pretty freaking awesome, huh?
Yeah, we know how good it looks. Thanks!
Luna seems to like the new family room couch
And the last picture of our apartment. See ya!
Lampost by the house. It was an early morning snow
The raw materials to for my new workbench and shelves
I cleared out the area, and so it begins!
:) Really coming together!
The bench is done!
Snowcalypse 2010: This is our front door from the inside
Keri leads the way! Lead on, brave girl!
Took me a while, but I found the car!!
Finally got to the back wheel of the CR-V. See that smaller car in the background? Yeah, my civic.
Very impressed that the deck is still standing :)
I found myself with 3 different mint teas and decided to taste test them and figure out which one I liked the most. Keri found this sad and humorous.
OK, so take two... three? Too much freaking snow!
One of the windows of a neighbor. The icicles almost touch the bottom!
Honestly, we are kinda hoping it will fall over by itself! :)
So this pile my neighbor and I created by pilling the snow from behind our cars. It is getting hard to pile it on!
It is a gorgeous day though!
Silly girl is actually considering going back in!
She broke it off from a group hanging outside our bedroom window and brought it down to show me :)
So we went out for lunch and to witness the aftermath as we had not left the house in a week!
The library, all icicly
That looks really cool
The Black Rock Center actually looks pretty good
And here is our quarry: an excellent sushi place
The yellow is a new circuit I added. All of the blue boxes are new as well. So much fun!
The mess of the breaker box before I installed the new breakers
The finished product: 6 outlets at the back of the workbench top, 4 in the ceiling for lighting attached to the light switch
As a point of reference, here is what the kitchen looked like before we bought it!
And there went the old counter top. Although we wound up just loving the white stripe where the backsplash was and decided to keep it instead of doing tile!
Sink is looking a little big... whoops!
And the finished product! The lighting sucked
Well, the glare sure does not do it justice...
Notice how close that faucet is to the window sill? It is out of pure luck that it actually fits (and it JUST fits).
A gratuitous picture of the new disposal and the new pvc pipping because it took me all night to fix.
Please accept this as the *after* picture for our tiling but the *before* picture for the work starting 6 pictures from here!
Previously we had several different items in this space. We bought these 3 units from Ikea to replace the previous furniture
Really need to get rid of that lamp!
We took out the useless recirculating hood along with the cabinet above it in order to install a shorter cabinet and a microwave

This is a lot like archaeology. Do you see the round hammer holes where the builder busted the wall looking for the electrical line he needed for the hood? I will be drywalling that and putting in a wall outlet for the microwave to use

Since I forgot to take a 
before picture, here are the components I removed :)
So, a man of my word, I cut out a much bigger and regularly shaped hole, added another 2x4 on the bottom and installed a wall outlet using the existing electrical line
And here is the patch with the first pass of mud!
We decided to tackle the front landscaping with more seriousness than last time. Keri went ahead and took out a whole tree by herself!
Ran into a small problem digging  a hole for an azalea. Stupid Verizon FIOS cable is buried a mere 4 inches from the top right through our flower bed
Not finished yet, but got 3 out of 4 bushes into the ground.
And here is the finished product, in daylight!
ARTSY!
Yeah, that is a bunch of dirt in the front. Really should take care of that...
And after that gardening break, we finally got aroung to trying to finish the installation of the new microwave
I obsessed over getting this bracket for the new microwave perfectly level. So I took a picture as photographic evidence
There you go!.... we might need to paint that cabinet.
One saturday afternoon we find ourselves with water dripping in our family room! Turns out a solenoid in the fridge directly above this ceiling broke and had been leaking for hours!
So that green piece in the background is the culprit in the infamous leak. I have the replacement in my hands.
The time has come to finally move this pipe so I can drywall this room! The pipe should have gone behind that beam but the plumber got a little lazy.
What am i doing?!
Keri is standing with bucket ready as water starts dribbling out of the cut.
Done! How about that? Thank you Kenny for the suggestion that I use Pex instead of copper :)
The second biggest piece left in the bathroom puzzle prior to drywalling: Installing the extractor!
Ok, the truly last addition before the drywall. This room got so hot while I was working, there was no way I could not add HVAC.
The shiny one is the new ducting I added for the bathroom. I went right into the the main duct from the furnace/ac and turned into the bathroom through the hallway ceiling.
So, it is time to drywall the damaged ceiling
We also took the opportunity to take out a chunk of the ceiling which we felt had been done incorrectly the first time around.
.... that is a really big hole...
Here we are. Drywall is up and just needs some mud!
